-trade-offs have been measured through field observations, through experimental manipulations in laboratory and field, through phenotypic correlations in laboratory and through genetic correlations
-most prominent life history trade off involves cost of reproduction: williams - genetic costs from antagonistic pleiotropy and negative phenotypic costs represented by negative correlations
-distinction made between intragenerational trade offs and intraindividual trade offs
-at time of publication, no known way to use current genetic structure of population to infer tradeoffs that constrained past approach to current state
-trade-offs at phenotypic level: whole organism measurements on traits directly connected to reproduction and survival
-trade-offs at genotypic level: all types of evidence claimed to be genetic (QG, mendelian, molecular genetics)

-2 important cases to consider
