-hormones affect many processes simultaneously and create patterns of correlation among responses
-antagonistic pleiotropy in the evolution of senscence - female hormones promote reproduction in early life, but involve disturbances to calcium metabolism in later life
-endocrine system mediated genetic correlations need to be examined more in research
-example of positive correlation observed in measurements of individuals for allocation of energy between reproduction and survival
-life history theory predicts that life history traits should be negatively correlated (see olijnyk nelson for references)
-genetic covariance sensitive to changes in gene frequencies and substitution of genes, so caution must be taken when claiming that negative correlations have relavence to historical path leading to current state
-2 questions: what constrains evolution (trade-offs relevant), and what produced patterns we see today?
-3 important questions about relationship between 2 traits: (1) is it positive or negative? (2) what is its shape? (3) what are its interactions with other traits and environmental factors?
-measure of curvature in trade-offs (Bell & Koufopanou 1986), eg rotifiers/ annual meadow grass


FOLLOW-UP
