@Article{Houle1992,
  author   = {Houle, D.},
  title    = {Comparing Evolvability and Variability of Quantitative Traits},
  journal  = {Genetics},
  year     = {1992},
  volume   = {130},
  number   = {1},
  pages    = {195--204},
  month    = jan,
  issn     = {0016-6731},
  abstract = {There are two distinct reasons for making comparisons of genetic variation for quantitative characters. The first is to compare evolvabilities, or ability to respond to selection, and the second is to make inferences about the forces that maintain genetic variability. Measures of variation that are standardized by the trait mean, such as the additive genetic coefficient of variation, are appropriate for both purposes. Variation has usually been compared as narrow sense heritabilities, but this is almost always an inappropriate comparative measure of evolvability and variability. Coefficients of variation were calculated from 842 estimates of trait means, variances and heritabilities in the literature. Traits closely related to fitness have higher additive genetic and nongenetic variability by the coefficient of variation criterion than characters under weak selection. This is the reverse of the accepted conclusion based on comparisons of heritability. The low heritability of fitness components is best explained by their high residual variation. The high additive genetic and residual variability of fitness traits might be explained by the great number of genetic and environmental events they are affected by, or by a lack of stabilizing selection to reduce their phenotypic variance. Over one-third of the quantitative genetics papers reviewed did not report trait means or variances. Researchers should always report these statistics, so that measures of variation appropriate to a variety of situations may be calculated.},
  comment  = {1301195[PII] 1732160[pmid]},
  database = {PMC},
  keywords = {rank1},
  review   = {QUESTION / HYPOTHESIS
-concerned with evolvability and maintenance of variation in quantitative traits and comparing them using mean standardized measures
-really pushes the idea of using "relative evolvability of fitness" to compare evolvability of traits
-really pushes the idea of using "coefficients of variation" to compare variances of different quantitative genetic traits

COMMENTS
-life history traits have lower narrow sense heritabilities, but h^2 is not appropriate measure of evolvability
-appropriate measure of "relative evolvability of fitness" denoted I_A is given by  I_A = V_A / X_bar^2 = (CV_A / 100)^2
-I_A also appropriate indicator of the variability of fitness, as large values must be result of powerful forces maintaining genetic variance
-CV_A seems a reasonable dimensionless criterion for comparing genetic variabilities (used by Charlesworth 1984, 1987)
-some problems exist with CV_A; ex. high standardized phenotypic variability might suggest lack of strong stablizing selection
-fitness components posses V_A (see follow up entry)

-reviewed quantiative genetic studies of animal populations, specifically data sets that met 5 criteria
1) characters assumed to be under strong directional selection, or weak stabilizing selection
2) population studied may be assumed to be near genetic equilibrium
3) population studied was outbred
4) additive genetic variance was estimated using relatively unbiased methods
5) variances are reported in untransformed scale

DISCUSSION
-Fitness traits tend to integrate variability over the lifetime of the organism, hence likely that larger number of loci, wider range of environmental variables, and more interaction among them affect fitness traits than morphological ones
-under most models of the maintenance of genetic variance, genetic variance in trait will tend to be correlated with the number of loci which affect it
-difficult to obtain precise estimates of genetic variance for traits with low h^2; 

FOLLOW-UP
-ISTOCK1 983; ROFFa nd MOUSSEAU1 987; MOUSSEAU and ROFF 1987 - V_A in the components of fitness

KEY TERMS
