DRIFT EXPLANATION: The small size of the selected and Control populations makes genetic drift a plausible alternative. This is apparently supported by the highly statistically significant difference between the G matrices of the Base and Control populations.  From basic drift calculation, the expect a 23% reduction in additive variance from drift. The qualitative conclusion is that although selection may well have altered the G matrices, the observed reduction in variances seem compatible with expectations from genetic drift alone.
	
BULMER EFFECT: are selection induced changes in G, will confound the effects and results from retrospective selection analysis.  They use a two trait simple model to compare the retrospective selection β_retro, with actual selection β_T after accounting for the Bulmer effect using eqtn (5).},
